// ch05 §5.16: "One-directional implicit conversion: not-unsafe-
// qualified -> unsafe-qualified only... it only ever *widens* the
// caller's obligation, never removes a real one." `add` is an ordinary
// (not-unsafe-qualified) function, yet it may still be stored in an
// `[[scpp::unsafe]]`-qualified pointer variable. Calling through that
// variable still requires `[[scpp::unsafe]] { }` regardless -- the
// obligation is driven by the *pointer's own type*, not by which
// function actually happens to be stored in it at runtime.
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    int (* [[scpp::unsafe]] up)(int, int) = add;
    int result{};
    [[scpp::unsafe]] {
        result = up(2, 3);
    }
    return result;
}
